04883nam a22008055i 9780812208726DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1024017143  a(OCoLC)979741198  a97808122087267 a10.9783/97808122087262doi  a(DE-B1597)449688  a(OCoLC)859160747  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a252/.05909742231 aNeuman, Meredith Marie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJeremiah's Scribes :bCreating Sermon Literature in Puritan New England /cMeredith Marie Neuman. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b9 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMaterial Texts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Transcription -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Unauthorizing the Sermon -- tChapter 2. Reading the Notetakers -- tChapter 3. Publishing Aurality -- tChapter 4. Crumbling, Collating, and Enabling -- tChapter 5. Narrating the Soul -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew England Puritan sermon culture was primarily an oral phenomenon, and yet its literary production has been understood mainly through a print legacy. In Jeremiah's Scribes, Meredith Marie Neuman turns to the notes taken by Puritan auditors in the meetinghouse in order to fill out our sense of the lived experience of the sermon. By reconstructing the aural culture of sermons, Neuman shifts our attention from the pulpit to the pew to demonstrate the many ways in which sermon auditors helped to shape this dominant genre of Puritan New England.Tracing the material transmission of sermon texts by readers and writers, hearers and notetakers, Jeremiah's Scribes challenges the notion of stable authorship by individual ministers. Instead, Neuman illuminates a mode of textual production that pervaded communities and occurred in the overlapping media of print, manuscript, and speech. Even printed sermons, she demonstrates, bore the traces of their roots in the oral culture of the meetinghouse.Bringing material considerations to bear on anxieties over the perceived relationship between divine and human language, Jeremiah's Scribes broadens our understanding of all Puritan literature. Neuman examines the controlling logic of the sermon in relation to nonsermonic writing—such as conversion narrative—ultimately suggesting the fundamental permeability among disparate genres of Puritan writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPuritansxReligious lifezNew England. 0aSermons, AmericanzNew EnglandxHistory and criticism. 0aTransmission of textszNew EnglandxHistoryy17th century. 4aReligious Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220872640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812208726423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812208726.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041354-0  Penn Press eBook-Package Literature  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL 